@page "/"

@using System.Globalization
@using FireCharts.Models

<PageTitle>Home</PageTitle>

<section class="home-hero">
    <div class="home-hero__copy">
        <p class="section-kicker">FireCharts component gallery</p>
        <div class="home-brand-lockup" aria-label="FireCharts brand">
            <img class="home-brand-lockup__mark" src="brand/concepts/firecharts-concept-2b.svg" alt="" />
            <div class="home-brand-lockup__copy">
                <p class="home-brand-lockup__title">FireCharts</p>
                <p class="home-brand-lockup__tagline">A Blazor forward chart library.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <h1>Show the library like a product, not just a demo list.</h1>
        <p class="hero-lede">
            The homepage now leads with the actual components: expressive charts, typed APIs, and interaction
            patterns that feel ready for dashboards, portals, and reporting surfaces.
        </p>

        <div class="home-hero__actions">
            <a class="button-link button-link--primary" href="linechart">See line chart demos</a>
            <a class="button-link" href="barchart">See bar chart demos</a>
            <a class="button-link" href="piechart">See pie chart demos</a>
        </div>

        <div class="home-hero__stats" aria-label="Library highlights">
            <div class="stat-pill">
                <strong>Typed components</strong>
                <span>Selector-based APIs keep data mapping explicit and easy to scan.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="stat-pill">
                <strong>Responsive by default</strong>
                <span>Examples flex from compact cards to wider dashboard canvases.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="stat-pill">
                <strong>Accessible interaction</strong>
                <span>Hover, focus, selection, and labels work together instead of competing.</span>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <aside class="home-hero__spotlight" aria-labelledby="home-spotlight-title">
        <div class="home-hero__spotlight-header">
            <div>
                <p class="section-kicker">Hero example</p>
                <h2 id="home-spotlight-title">Operational trend preview</h2>
            </div>
            <p class="home-hero__spotlight-copy">
                A live line chart in the hero makes the library feel tangible immediately.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="chart-scroll">
            <FireLineChart TItem="HeroTrendPoint"
                           Title="Inspections completed"
                           Description="Weekly inspections completed across four service areas"
                           Width="640"
                           Height="360"
                           Responsive="true"
                           Series="@HeroTrendSeries"
                           XValueSelector="point => LineChartXValue.FromDateTime(point.Date)"
                           YValueSelector="point => point.Value"
                           LabelSelector="point => point.Label"
                           HighlightSelector="point => point.Highlight"
                           ShowLegend="true"
                           PointDisplayMode="@LinePointDisplayMode.HighlightedOnly">
                <TooltipTemplate Context="point">
                    <div class="demo-tooltip-title">@point.SeriesName</div>
                    <div>@point.X.ToDateTime().ToString("MMM d", CultureInfo.InvariantCulture)</div>
                    <div>@point.Y.ToString("F0", CultureInfo.InvariantCulture) completed</div>
                </TooltipTemplate>
            </FireLineChart>
        </div>
    </aside>
</section>

<section class="home-value" aria-label="Why this library feels product ready">
    <article class="feature-card">
        <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Real components</p>
        <h2>Examples sell the API</h2>
        <p>Each preview is a real component instance, so the homepage feels like a showroom instead of static marketing copy.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="feature-card">
        <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Consistent patterns</p>
        <h2>One mental model across charts</h2>
        <p>Selectors, titles, descriptions, and responsive behavior stay familiar whether you render bars, lines, or pies.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="feature-card">
        <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Dashboard friendly</p>
        <h2>Strong in cards and full pages</h2>
        <p>The same components can anchor a landing page, sit in a dense admin grid, or expand into dedicated demo pages.</p>
    </article>
</section>

<section class="home-showcase">
    <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="section-kicker">Component showcase</p>
        <h2>Three chart types, each presented like a polished product feature.</h2>
        <p class="section-lede">
            The homepage now introduces the library through compact, high-signal examples and a short explanation of
            where each component shines.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="home-showcase__grid">
        <ChartDemoCard Kicker="Line chart"
                       Title="Trend stories with highlighted moments"
                       Description="Use smooth, precise trend lines for operational volume, throughput, adoption, or any time-based signal."
                       Compact="true">
            <ChildContent>
                <FireLineChart TItem="MiniTrendPoint"
                               Title="Permit intake"
                               Description="Weekly permit intake"
                               Width="420"
                               Height="300"
                               Responsive="true"
                               Items="@MiniTrend"
                               XValueSelector="point => LineChartXValue.FromDateTime(point.Date)"
                               YValueSelector="point => point.Value"
                               LabelSelector="point => point.Label"
                               HighlightSelector="point => point.Highlight"
                               ShowLegend="false"
                               PointDisplayMode="@LinePointDisplayMode.HighlightedOnly" />
            </ChildContent>
            <FooterContent>
                <div class="home-card-footer">
                    <span class="home-chip">Smooth or step interpolation</span>
                    <span class="home-chip">Optional selection state</span>
                </div>
            </FooterContent>
        </ChartDemoCard>

        <ChartDemoCard Kicker="Bar chart"
                       Title="Category comparisons with confident labels"
                       Description="Bar charts work well for ranking, inventory, throughput, and side-by-side comparisons that need quick scanning."
                       Compact="true">
            <ChildContent>
                <FireBarChart TItem="MiniBarPoint"
                              Title="Service requests"
                              Description="Requests by category"
                              Width="420"
                              Height="300"
                              Responsive="true"
                              Items="@MiniBars"
                              ValueSelector="point => point.Value"
                              LabelSelector="point => point.Label"
                              ColorSelector="point => point.Color"
                              HoverColorSelector="point => point.HoverColor"
                              GridLineCount="4"
                              BarSpacing="0.18" />
            </ChildContent>
            <FooterContent>
                <div class="home-card-footer">
                    <span class="home-chip">Vertical or horizontal layout</span>
                    <span class="home-chip">Value labels and tooltips</span>
                </div>
            </FooterContent>
        </ChartDemoCard>

        <ChartDemoCard Kicker="Pie chart"
                       Title="Composition views with calm radial labeling"
                       Description="Show allocation, share, or channel mix using overlay labels or a cleaner legend-first treatment."
                       Compact="true"
                       WrapInScroll="false">
            <ChildContent>
                <FirePieChart TItem="MiniSlice"
                              Title="Request channels"
                              Description="Volume by intake channel"
                              Width="420"
                              Height="320"
                              Responsive="true"
                              Items="@MiniSlices"
                              ValueSelector="point => point.Value"
                              LabelSelector="point => point.Label"
                              ColorSelector="point => point.Color"
                              InnerRadiusRatio="0.34"
                              LabelMode="PieChartLabelMode.Legend"
                              ShowCenterLabel="true"
                              CenterLabelTitle="Channels" />
            </ChildContent>
            <FooterContent>
                <div class="home-card-footer">
                    <span class="home-chip">Pie or donut styling</span>
                    <span class="home-chip">Overlay or legend labels</span>
                </div>
            </FooterContent>
        </ChartDemoCard>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="home-api">
    <div class="home-api__content">
        <p class="section-kicker">Developer experience</p>
        <h2>The API surface stays approachable even when the visuals feel premium.</h2>
        <p class="section-lede">
            The examples below market the library to both audiences at once: designers see polished output, and
            developers can tell the components are straightforward to wire up.
        </p>

        <div class="home-api__list" aria-label="API qualities">
            <div class="home-api__item">
                <strong>Typed data in</strong>
                <span>Keep your own models and map them with selectors instead of reshaping everything into a chart DTO.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="home-api__item">
                <strong>Behavior toggles</strong>
                <span>Turn on legends, labels, grid lines, interpolation modes, and selection without custom renderers.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="home-api__item">
                <strong>Composable templates</strong>
                <span>Drop in tooltip content where richer storytelling or dashboard context is useful.</span>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <article class="docs-card docs-card--code home-code-card">
        <div class="chart-card__header">
            <div>
                <p class="section-kicker">Starter snippet</p>
                <h3>Render a showcase-ready chart</h3>
            </div>
            <p class="chart-card__copy">The same patterns from the demo pages work cleanly in product code.</p>
        </div>

        <pre class="code-example"><code>@HomeUsageExample</code></pre>
    </article>
</section>

